{
  "texts": [
    "First, with higher p and lower q, the article leads to stronger belief updates, which then generates more polarized posterior beliefs.",
    "Second, when content is more divisive, it becomes more profitable for the platform to opt for a filter bubble, as shown in Proposition 3 of Acemoglu, Ozdaglar, and Siderius (2024), and via this choice of platform architecture, more divisive content again promotes polarization.",
    "Finally, we can also study the implications of the prior distribution of the electorate becoming more polarized.",
    "According to Proposition 3 in Acemoglu, Ozdaglar, and Siderius (2024), when prior polarization becomes stronger, filter bubbles become more likely, which further drives belief polarization by Proposition 4.3, and in turn, party polarization by Corollary 4.1.",
    "In this sense, polarization is like \"Pandora's box\": once the electorate becomes polarized, social media fuels the flames of polarization through the AI's choice of algorithm, which further reinforces the polarization."
  ]
}